00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:43.980
Which is why this session is called
Cutting Edge Interface Design.

00:01:44.460 --> 00:01:48.140
I hope no one bleeds in this session,
and we'll have a lot of fun.

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:50.300
And the point of the whole thing
is to teach you guys how to

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:51.500
create really great products.

00:01:53.550 --> 00:01:56.820
Alright, we're going to go about this
with sort of three major steps.

00:01:56.820 --> 00:02:01.300
Alright, to create a really great
product on the platform,

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:06.040
which of course is going to have a great,
you know, sensational user interface,

00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:09.270
you need to start with something,
you need to start by

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:11.280
defining your product.

00:02:11.330 --> 00:02:15.890
And defining your product is deciding
what to do and who to do it for.

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:20.380
The first step in this process
is understanding your users.

00:02:20.510 --> 00:02:23.260
If you were in this session last year,
I touched on some of this content.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:25.500
Don't worry, this will not be a repeat
of last year's session.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:28.630
But this stuff is so important,
I want to cover it again.

00:02:28.630 --> 00:02:31.670
Understanding your user base is critical.

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.250
And this doesn't mean you
have to do $100,000 studies,

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:39.090
doesn't mean you have to get two-way
labs with mirrors and all this stuff,

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:41.060
like you may have read about elsewhere.

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:44.020
It just means taking the time
to do the analysis and think

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:45.810
about who your customers are.

00:02:46.330 --> 00:02:47.370
What are their goals?

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:51.160
What do they hope to accomplish with
the product that you're building?

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:52.500
Right?

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:53.740
What is their workflow?

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:54.920
What are they trying to finish?

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:56.530
You know, at the end of the day,
what's the problem that

00:02:56.530 --> 00:02:57.250
they're trying to do?

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:58.250
What are their needs?

00:02:58.490 --> 00:03:01.060
What's required for them
to get the task done,

00:03:01.060 --> 00:03:01.910
basically?

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:04.260
Don't try to be everything for everybody.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:08.230
Figure out exactly what you want to do,
what your product is going to do,

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:11.580
and develop it
specifically for that goal.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:14.140
Users often don't know what they want.

00:03:14.210 --> 00:03:16.570
If you're in consulting,
you know what it's like to talk

00:03:16.570 --> 00:03:18.810
to a customer and they say,
oh yeah, here's the spec,

00:03:18.810 --> 00:03:20.710
you need to build this and
that and the other thing,

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:23.610
and so you go off and, you know,
like a good contractor, you build it,

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:25.200
and then you show it to them.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:26.050
What happens?

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:27.660
That's not what they wanted.

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:32.740
Well, that's because the whole design
process is a really complicated thing

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:36.010
where people tend to have to look
at something tangible and interact

00:03:36.130 --> 00:03:39.690
with it and then they realize,
oh no, this isn't what I wanted.

00:03:39.700 --> 00:07:32.400
[Transcript missing]

00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:38.750
Once you understand the market
you're going to go after,

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:42.260
and you've kind of hit the bullet points
of which attributes you want to aim for,

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:45.430
then it's critical for you to
sort of prioritize those things.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:47.660
Because at the end of the day,
you've got a bunch of work to do,

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:50.220
and you've got to decide what you're
going to do first and what you could

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:51.990
potentially leave off to the end,
right?

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.230
Now I would say, you know, first, second,
and third priority items,

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:58.020
none of those get dropped to
the end or left off entirely.

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:01.180
But it's just a great
exercise to go through.

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:02.950
This is not a big academic thing.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:05.280
It's just take the time,
get the right people in the room,

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:07.740
talk about these things,
and let these things start

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:09.470
to drive your product design.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.040
So, understand your users,
understand the market,

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:17.390
determine the attributes you want
to go after with your product,

00:08:17.410 --> 00:08:18.360
prioritize those things.

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:20.060
The next thing is understand yourself.

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:23.450
Figure out what your strengths
are and what your weaknesses are.

00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:25.510
Who can you partner with?

00:08:25.730 --> 00:08:28.790
Determine who you can partner
with to leverage their strengths.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:32.160
You take the guys at
Delicious Monster with Delicious Library.

00:08:32.160 --> 00:08:35.000
They decided that their
expertise was one thing,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.670
and that if they wanted to
get information about books

00:08:37.860 --> 00:08:40.150
and DVDs and CDs or whatever,
that they would go out

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:41.240
and partner with Amazon.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:43.900
Perfect partnership.

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.360
What do you do?

00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:48.780
What does your product do that really,
at the end of the day,

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:49.690
is not your strength?

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:52.500
Find those areas and
get rid of that code.

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:54.480
Partner with somebody else
who does it real well.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:56.660
At the end of the day,
you'll have a partnership of innovators,

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:59.170
or a partnership of, you know,
kind of like the Apple Intel thing.

00:08:59.170 --> 00:09:01.690
Get the right people
together on the project,

00:09:01.690 --> 00:09:04.760
and you're going to have a
better product as a result.

00:09:06.670 --> 00:09:08.640
Another thing to do is
look at other successful

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:10.920
applications or the competition.

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:12.720
What are they doing right?

00:09:12.770 --> 00:09:14.280
What are they not doing right?

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:17.620
What can you take advantage of
in terms of their weaknesses?

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:20.200
And if they're doing something right,
why are they doing that right?

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:21.870
What do they know that you don't know?

00:09:21.920 --> 00:09:24.290
All of this analysis,
this doesn't take years.

00:09:24.390 --> 00:09:26.260
This is-- you know,
you can do this quickly.

00:09:26.330 --> 00:09:29.850
But a lot of companies I meet with,
when I ask these basic questions, I say,

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:30.560
who are your competition?

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:32.060
Oh, they state the competition.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:34.820
I say, well, so what are their strengths?

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:38.820
Well, what are you guys good at?

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:40.880
Write some Cocoa code, or whatever.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:44.720
So I'm going to joke around,
but I've seen a lot of companies

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:46.000
I've been with do great stuff.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.540
But I like kidding
around in this session.

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:49.520
All right, so you've done all that stuff.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.690
Now the question is, all right,
start to define the solution.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:54.020
You've all got great ideas.

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:57.060
I don't think I've met with a single
company over the last five and a half

00:09:57.060 --> 00:09:58.660
years that didn't have a good idea.

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:00.050
Maybe one.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.920
But when you start to define,
you've got a great idea.

00:10:03.920 --> 00:10:08.040
You're very, very-- there's lots of
great ideas out there.

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:11.820
Now the challenge is, all right,
so what is this idea?

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.760
How is it going to become a product?

00:10:13.780 --> 00:10:15.720
What is it really going to do?

00:10:15.750 --> 00:10:18.140
What are the problems it's
really going to solve?

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:22.470
And then a really great exercise
is to work cross-functionally

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:25.880
as a team and define a mission
statement for your product.

00:10:26.150 --> 00:10:28.860
I put it here as a product
definition statement.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:31.580
But a mission statement for your product.

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:32.220
And then hang it up.

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:32.850
Print it out.

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:34.500
Hang it up amongst the design team.

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:37.480
And everything you do should come
back to that mission statement.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:40.460
Every feature you consider,
every aspect of the product

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:43.500
should be run through the filter
of that mission statement to say,

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:47.040
hey, hey, hey,
is this really part of this product?

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:48.520
Is this really what we meant it to be?

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:50.740
Does this need to be here?

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:53.440
The tendency is, as you guys know,
I'm sure,

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:59.030
the tendency is to fall victim to the
need to kind of glom on another feature,

00:10:59.030 --> 00:11:00.000
like, oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:04.450
Hey, somebody wanted this thing,
let's put this new feature on.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:05.780
And it kind of gets glommed on.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:07.660
And at first, you don't notice it.

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.040
But after you develop a product,
a couple revisions,

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:12.700
and you've done it that way,
suddenly you think, man,

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:15.680
we're getting-- it's
kind of out of control.

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.380
Or it's just not what we thought
it was going to be originally.

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:21.540
And so this is a great way
to keep yourself in line.

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:26.050
Keep in mind things like usability,
efficiency, the desired workflow.

00:11:26.060 --> 00:11:27.520
How are your customers going
to work with this thing?

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.600
And what other applications
does the product interact with?

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:34.660
Do you need drag and drop
interaction with-- Final Cut Pro?

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:36.060
Or do you need cut, copy, paste?

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:39.100
Or how does data move from your
product to the other products?

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:43.090
And if it doesn't,
then maybe you can drop the need

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:44.050
for some of that functionality.

00:11:44.150 --> 00:11:47.490
So anyway, lots of stuff to do.

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:48.900
Last thing is keep things simple.

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:50.140
We're going to go through
this stuff in detail.

00:11:50.140 --> 00:11:51.060
But keep things simple.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:54.100
Boil down the large
concepts to their essence,

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:56.720
to small, discrete functionality.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:59.500
The tendency is to say, hey,
we've got this great idea.

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:02.630
And then suddenly-- actually,
there's a great-- let me just

00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:03.840
illustrate this with a cartoon.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:06.020
I saw it one time years ago.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:07.620
And it was this comic strip.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:10.380
And there were a bunch of guys,
people sitting at computers.

00:12:10.380 --> 00:12:12.240
And they're ready to code.

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:13.850
And the boss is going out the door.

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:17.060
And he says, you guys get coding.

00:12:17.060 --> 00:12:19.780
I'll go upstairs and see
what they want us to make.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:22.040
And too often, that's the case.

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:23.820
So get these ideas down.

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:25.100
Figure out who your customer base is.

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:27.020
Figure out who your market segment is.

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:30.140
And then define a mission
statement and go from there.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:35.140
And anyway, so at that point,
you've got a good idea.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:36.290
You understand all those things.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:39.370
You've got a sense for what the
product is very specifically.

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:43.000
Now you start to figure out, well,
what's your feature set?

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:46.200
How will the product work specifically?

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:51.120
If you're a time billing product
or you're a music player,

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:53.400
well,
what functionality do you want to have?

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:55.280
And that's where we start
to bring in the features.

00:12:55.310 --> 00:13:00.160
Define the core set of features required,
but avoid feature cascade.

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:03.060
Don't just glom on things and
look at the competition and say,

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:05.790
oh, we have to do everything they do.

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:08.620
When it comes down to it,
some of the best products

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.670
today on Mac OS X,
for that matter, some of the best

00:13:11.830 --> 00:13:14.560
products in the industry,
most usable products in the industry,

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:17.490
are not the most full-featured
products in the world.

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:19.080
You take the iPod.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:20.450
Why is the iPod successful?

00:13:20.510 --> 00:13:22.680
Yes, it's got great marketing behind it.

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:24.800
Yes,
it's got a great music store behind it.

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:28.580
But at the end of the day,
the iPod is what it is because it does

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:31.240
exactly what everyone wants it to do.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:34.100
Is it the most full-featured
music player in the world?

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:36.560
Does it have the most wheels
and dials and buttons?

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:38.180
No, but it doesn't matter.

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:41.740
No one cares because they want
this music player to do just what

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:43.960
it does and it does it perfectly.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:49.070
Is iTunes the most full-featured
music jukebox software in the world?

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:49.820
Not at all.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:52.530
There's lots of other products
out there that have way more

00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:53.990
bells and whistles on them.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:16:02.700
[Transcript missing]

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:55.300
[Transcript missing]

00:16:55.600 --> 00:17:18.700
[Transcript missing]

00:17:19.270 --> 00:17:21.930
For new users,
it wasn't intuitive enough.

00:17:21.930 --> 00:17:25.570
We found that people that were
new to the product were spending

00:17:25.570 --> 00:17:29.140
too much time looking for the
common commands they needed.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:32.500
They were spending too much
time trying to find things.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:35.150
They were getting lost
in the user interface.

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:37.850
They were having trouble finding things.

00:17:37.880 --> 00:17:39.770
So that needed to be solved.

00:17:39.820 --> 00:17:43.770
And finally,
our user interface was showing its age.

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:48.320
You know, we shipped our version one
of our product in 1998.

00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:52.950
And the user interface that we
designed at that time was appropriate

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:55.730
for the user interface of that time.

00:17:55.740 --> 00:17:58.570
Well, things have changed
dramatically since then.

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:01.420
I mean, the user interface of Mac OS X,
for example,

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:05.320
is dramatically different from the
user interface of classic Mac OS.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:09.800
So we needed to bring our user interface,
you know, to the market.

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:12.310
you know, into the modern age.

00:18:12.980 --> 00:18:16.770
So this is our previous version,
Real Basic 5.5.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:21.800
And it's got a lot of windows and
we carbonized it and we made it,

00:18:21.800 --> 00:18:23.450
gave it the Aqua user interface.

00:18:23.460 --> 00:18:26.980
But the thing is,
is the Aqua user interface isn't the same

00:18:26.990 --> 00:18:29.400
thing as the Mac OS X user experience.

00:18:29.460 --> 00:18:31.020
Those aren't the same thing at all.

00:18:31.030 --> 00:18:33.140
Aqua is just a component of that.

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:37.700
So it's not enough to simply
give it the Aqua interface.

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:41.350
You've got to think about what is
the user expecting on Mac OS X.

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:43.460
And this is not what they're expecting.

00:18:43.460 --> 00:18:48.420
So we decided that this needed a
change and needed a dramatic change.

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:49.630
So this is what we came up with.

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:52.840
This is the version that we're going
to be shipping later this month.

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:56.290
It's a single document window.

00:18:56.290 --> 00:18:59.310
It has a toolbar,
which we didn't have before.

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:01.250
Actually, it has a couple of toolbars.

