00:28:14.830 --> 00:28:18.120
So what did we learn going
through this process?

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:23.300
Well, first we learned that we
need to watch our users.

00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:24.840
You need to watch what
your users are doing.

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:25.930
John said this earlier.

00:28:25.930 --> 00:28:27.060
Watch how they work.

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:32.260
You don't need a $10,000
or $100,000 lab to do this.

00:28:32.260 --> 00:28:36.490
You don't need two-way mirrors and
video cameras and all the scientific

00:28:36.630 --> 00:28:39.080
way of monitoring what a person does.

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:42.640
Bring them into your conference
room and just sit next to them

00:28:42.710 --> 00:28:44.300
and watch them use your product.

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:47.640
You will see when they get
frustrated or when they're confused.

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.940
And we did this ourselves.

00:28:49.940 --> 00:28:51.720
We brought users into
our conference room.

00:28:51.720 --> 00:28:53.140
We sat there and watched them work.

00:28:53.220 --> 00:28:55.660
New users and experienced users.

00:28:55.660 --> 00:28:59.750
And we were surprised at
the things we learned.

00:29:00.550 --> 00:29:04.160
I guarantee you, if you do this,
you better have a pad of paper or

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:08.020
you better be the world's fastest
typist because you're not going to

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:10.320
be able to take notes fast enough.

00:29:10.380 --> 00:29:13.560
You're going to actually ask people,
could you stop for a second because I'm

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:15.210
not able to write all this stuff down.

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:17.920
You're going to learn a tremendous
amount about your product,

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:19.260
about your user interface.

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:24.190
Don't be afraid to make big changes.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:27.540
You know, as developers,
we pour our blood, sweat,

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:29.380
and tears into building our products.

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:35.600
And we love the way we do things,
and we've poured a lot of energy into it.

00:29:35.650 --> 00:29:37.400
But that's not really what's important.

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:38.620
I mean, it's great to do that.

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:41.470
But at the end of the day,
what's important is that

00:29:41.550 --> 00:29:43.030
the product be usable.

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:46.340
I mean, we're not doing this out of
the kindness of our hearts.

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:47.590
We want to make money.

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:51.460
So the more usable your product is,
the more intuitive it is,

00:29:51.820 --> 00:29:54.080
the more of it you're going to sell.

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:55.320
So that's really important.

00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:57.820
And in our case,
there was really no way for us

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:02.100
to make incremental changes to
arrive at what we needed to have,

00:30:02.150 --> 00:30:04.120
this new user interface.

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:05.950
We really had to make a dramatic change.

00:30:05.960 --> 00:30:06.990
And we accepted that.

00:30:07.210 --> 00:30:09.190
We spent two years doing it.

00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:13.820
And in fact, as a side note,
the previous version's user

00:30:13.820 --> 00:30:17.510
interface was written in C++ on top
of our cross-platform framework.

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:21.560
This version, Real Basic 2005,
is written in Real Basic.

00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:24.040
So when people ask us, well,
give me an example of what

00:30:24.040 --> 00:30:28.620
you can do with Real Basic,
now we can say, well, Real Basic.

00:30:28.790 --> 00:30:31.690
So don't be afraid to make big changes.

00:30:32.170 --> 00:30:34.150
Consider the knowledge
the user already has.

00:30:34.150 --> 00:30:35.470
I mentioned this earlier.

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:39.700
It's not always the best thing to do.

00:30:39.700 --> 00:30:42.080
It may be creative,
but it's not always the best thing to do

00:30:42.140 --> 00:30:43.960
to invent some new way of doing things.

00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:47.060
Sometimes it's good to innovate,
but other times it's

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:48.580
good to be consistent.

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:50.940
And consistency really should come first.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:55.100
If there is no consistent
way of doing something,

00:30:55.100 --> 00:30:56.840
well then you're going to have
to come up with something new.

00:30:56.840 --> 00:31:00.460
But if there is a way that
the user is used to working,

00:31:00.460 --> 00:31:01.620
then do that.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:04.010
I mean,
imagine if you got into an automobile

00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:08.180
and the steering wheel was different and
the way you shifted gears was different

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:10.040
and the way you turned on blinkers.

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:13.290
I mean, you can get into any car and
immediately use it because you're

00:31:13.350 --> 00:31:15.240
reusing knowledge you have,
right?

00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:18.200
It would be very frustrating
if it didn't work that way.

00:31:18.200 --> 00:31:20.270
Well, software is exactly the same way.

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:24.360
And I think that Apple has got
to be the kings of consistency

00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:26.800
and excellent user interface.

00:31:26.900 --> 00:31:32.570
So, look at what knowledge the user
has and reuse that knowledge.

00:31:33.930 --> 00:31:36.390
Read Apple's Human Interface Guidelines.

00:31:36.390 --> 00:31:39.460
The guidelines aren't just
examples of what to do.

00:31:39.810 --> 00:31:44.040
They don't necessarily say this,
but there was a tremendous amount of

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:49.580
thought and care and logic that went
into the user interface guidelines.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:54.370
That logic may not be presented
in the document itself,

00:31:54.370 --> 00:31:58.180
but trust me, it's all behind the scenes.

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:00.370
Read the Human Interface Guidelines.

00:32:00.370 --> 00:32:01.340
Know them well.

00:32:01.340 --> 00:32:03.050
You'll learn a lot from that.

00:32:04.620 --> 00:32:05.500
and visit the H.I.

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:06.590
Lab.

00:32:06.590 --> 00:32:07.500
John mentioned this earlier.

00:32:07.500 --> 00:32:08.560
It's down the hall.

00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:11.660
You can sit down with user
interface experts at Apple.

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:14.500
They'll give you plenty
of great feedback.

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:20.450
A couple times during the
development of our user interface,

00:32:20.450 --> 00:32:23.500
we sat down with John Geleynsse,
which we really appreciate, John.

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:27.350
He went over the entire user interface
with us and gave us a tremendous

00:32:27.430 --> 00:32:31.500
amount of feedback on big things,
on little things.

00:32:31.500 --> 00:32:35.500
There was a lot of stuff that we would
have missed if we hadn't done that.

00:32:35.500 --> 00:32:38.620
As developers,
Apple provides this to you,

00:32:38.620 --> 00:32:40.340
so take advantage of it.

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:43.500
John said not everyone is
an expert at everything.

00:32:43.500 --> 00:32:45.390
That's absolutely true.

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:51.410
You're not necessarily going to be an
expert at user interface right away.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:53.490
The people at Apple are.

00:32:53.490 --> 00:32:55.500
Take advantage of that resource.

00:32:58.400 --> 00:33:01.290
So I'd like to thank you
for having me here today,

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:05.140
John,
and enjoy the rest of the conference.

00:33:11.300 --> 00:33:12.000
All right, that's great.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.060
I'd like to invite one
other guy on stage.

00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:16.230
Adam Baker is an intern
for me a couple years ago.

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:19.450
He's going to talk quickly about
what they did with their product,

00:33:19.450 --> 00:33:23.840
and then we're going to get into
some cutting-edge bleeding stuff.

00:33:25.300 --> 00:33:27.200
Thank you, John.

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:29.700
So, as John mentioned,
I am a user interface

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:32.640
designer for Market Circle,
and we just released a

00:33:32.640 --> 00:33:35.660
product called Billings,
which as you may be able to tell from

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:38.670
the icon is a time billing application.

00:33:38.740 --> 00:33:43.560
So you can track your time,
send invoices, track payments, and so on.

00:33:44.160 --> 00:33:46.940
So this is Billings' main window,
and it's not especially

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:50.100
exciting software because it's
basically accounting software.

00:33:50.100 --> 00:33:54.100
You know,
this is not really glamorous stuff.

00:33:54.410 --> 00:33:57.400
Nevertheless,
somewhat mundane or boring software

00:33:57.400 --> 00:33:59.100
can still be well designed.

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:01.050
And we think that Billings works.

00:34:01.110 --> 00:34:03.050
Now the question is
how does Billings work,

00:34:03.050 --> 00:34:04.100
or why does it work?

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:07.520
And when we looked at the competition,
we found that they were

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:09.100
just too complicated.

00:34:09.100 --> 00:34:12.100
So our goal was to keep Billings simple.

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:14.880
Now this is also kind of misleading
because keeping something

00:34:14.890 --> 00:34:17.100
simple is harder than it looks.

00:34:17.100 --> 00:34:20.100
It's really about focus.

00:34:20.630 --> 00:34:24.060
So, focus is really about saying
no to things that don't belong,

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:26.460
rather than finding the right
thing and saying yes to that.

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:29.040
It's about saying this doesn't belong.

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:32.240
One way to frame your
application to focus it is to

00:34:32.240 --> 00:34:33.520
ask a few questions about it.

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:35.250
The first is who's going to use it?

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:39.180
John and Jeff talked about this already.

00:34:39.180 --> 00:34:39.180
This is the most important step.

00:34:39.380 --> 00:34:40.840
Then find out what will it be.

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:42.930
This is really talking
about the functionality,

00:34:42.930 --> 00:34:46.330
what the application will
do for these customers.

00:34:47.020 --> 00:34:48.440
And next is how will it work?

00:34:48.510 --> 00:34:52.530
And this really is about the actual
user interface of the product.

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:55.590
So in the case of Billings,
the first thing we had to find out

00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:56.860
was who's going to use this product.

00:34:56.950 --> 00:34:59.500
We had to identify our users.

00:34:59.590 --> 00:35:02.120
And one thing that we knew
about our users is that they're

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:04.600
independent professionals who
track and build their time.

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:08.560
So these are people like lawyers,
like designers, like housing contractors.

00:35:08.690 --> 00:35:09.700
They do work.

00:35:09.770 --> 00:35:11.540
They work at a particular hourly wage.

00:35:11.700 --> 00:35:15.180
They need to send accurate
invoices to their customers.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:18.070
We know that they spend most of
their time in other applications

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:19.600
or not on the Mac at all.

00:35:19.620 --> 00:35:21.600
Which means that in
the case of a designer,

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:23.710
for instance,
she might spend 8 hours a day,

00:35:23.720 --> 00:35:26.750
or 7 hours a day,
or 12 hours a day in QuarkXPress,

00:35:26.750 --> 00:35:28.600
in Photoshop, in InDesign.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:31.270
You know,
Billings is going to be a secondary app,

00:35:31.270 --> 00:35:34.150
even though it's doing
something very important.

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:38.820
Our users aren't accountants,
so they may not be familiar

00:35:38.820 --> 00:35:41.660
with accounting terms,
they may not like keeping

00:35:41.730 --> 00:35:44.200
track of expense receipts,
and making up invoices,

00:35:44.200 --> 00:35:46.300
and calculating taxes,
and markup and discount.

00:35:46.300 --> 00:35:47.800
This is not fun stuff.

00:35:47.800 --> 00:35:49.300
Some people aren't very good at math.

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:52.300
Programs should do this for them.

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:57.260
Understanding the users leads
to this concept of a solution.

00:35:57.750 --> 00:36:00.560
Going point by point,
our users need a solution that

00:36:00.560 --> 00:36:02.200
makes time tracking simple.

00:36:02.250 --> 00:36:04.310
It needs to be easy.

00:36:05.180 --> 00:36:07.170
They need something that's
easy to learn and lightweight.

00:36:07.320 --> 00:36:09.970
In the case of the designer,
remember that our

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:11.650
application is secondary.

00:36:11.800 --> 00:36:14.620
If it takes up a lot of
screen real estate or if it's

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:18.400
very imposing on the user,
they're going to find that it gets

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:20.800
in the way of their normal workflow.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:24.100
So in our case, we do have a main window,
a big window,

00:36:24.130 --> 00:36:27.100
but the core functionality is
provided in a smaller window,

00:36:27.100 --> 00:36:29.400
a timer window,
that floats above all other

00:36:29.400 --> 00:36:33.200
applications or can be hidden
completely and still run.

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:36.200
And the most important thing, perhaps,
in a case like this,

00:36:36.250 --> 00:36:39.200
really has very little to do
with user interface per se,

00:36:39.260 --> 00:36:41.500
but everything to do
with user experience,

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:44.100
which is that the solution
that we came up with had to do

00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:46.400
the heavy lifting for users.

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:49.100
So users aren't doing the
accounting themselves.

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:51.810
Billings is doing the
accounting for them.

00:36:52.900 --> 00:36:57.060
Second question, what will Billings do,
is all about defining the functionality.

00:36:57.190 --> 00:36:59.940
So a very common way of
developing is to come up with

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:02.520
a list of features like this.

00:37:02.570 --> 00:37:06.320
So an application like Billings needs
to do all of this stuff and more.

00:37:06.380 --> 00:37:10.130
But it's almost impossible
to look at this and distill a

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:14.420
really compact statement that
describes what the solution is.

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:17.160
Yet you could begin with this
and actually implement all of

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:18.770
these features one at a time.

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:22.110
You could string them together
into some kind of user interface.

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:24.840
Best thing to do,
as John already mentioned,

00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:26.800
is to come up with a mission statement.

00:37:26.850 --> 00:37:31.210
In our case, all of these features can
be condensed into estimates,

00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:34.600
time tracking, and invoicing for the
Mac-based professional.

00:37:34.750 --> 00:37:35.870
This is our solution.

00:37:35.870 --> 00:37:36.860
This is like a box.

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:39.140
We know what stuff goes in the box.

00:37:39.140 --> 00:37:41.920
We know things that
don't belong in the box.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.710
The last part, how will Billings work?

00:37:44.790 --> 00:37:47.330
This is really about the
user interface design,

00:37:47.340 --> 00:37:50.340
and so I'm not going to go into
detail about what we did per se,

00:37:50.340 --> 00:37:51.640
but I'll share with you some tips.

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:55.640
If you want to see what we ended up with,
you can download Billings.

00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:59.340
So I figured that there are
three big tips I can share with

00:37:59.430 --> 00:38:02.870
you that came out of what we
learned when we're doing Billings.

00:38:02.980 --> 00:38:05.110
The first is to think Aqua.

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:09.240
As Jeff mentioned,
Aqua and the whole Mac OS X user

00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:11.640
experience is something
that is very complete.

00:38:11.640 --> 00:38:13.510
It's got a very specific feel.

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:17.400
And a lot of work has been done by
other developers and by Apple to come

00:38:17.400 --> 00:38:20.640
up with the human interface guidelines,
great examples of applications.

00:38:20.700 --> 00:38:22.350
So thinking Aqua is really important.

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:25.470
If your app doesn't look and
feel like a Mac OS X application,

00:38:25.480 --> 00:38:27.990
users will reject it right away.

00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:31.700
Second tip is to design on paper.

00:38:31.720 --> 00:38:33.900
And the third tip is to keep
learning proportional to your

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:35.540
application's importance.

00:38:35.660 --> 00:38:38.340
This is also really, really important.

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:41.950
If your application is like Billings,
one that people use

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:44.100
maybe 10 minutes a day,
you don't want to make

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:45.060
it difficult to learn.

00:38:45.060 --> 00:38:47.660
People need to be able to get
in and out really quickly.

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:50.510
But, you know,
there's a big focus on ease of use and

00:38:50.510 --> 00:38:53.700
you might feel that if your application
is one that people use all day,

00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:56.200
that it's the main
part of their business,

00:38:56.330 --> 00:38:58.710
that you don't,
it might be confusing to you to

00:38:58.710 --> 00:39:00.300
say it needs to be easy to use.

00:39:00.410 --> 00:39:03.100
You know, this is a complicated app,
it does all of these complicated things

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:04.780
and it's really helpful to our users.

00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:07.140
In that case,
people will be willing to learn

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:10.260
more about your application because
it's their bread and butter.

00:39:10.320 --> 00:39:13.280
But in the case of something like
a calculator or time tracking app,

00:39:13.370 --> 00:39:16.300
you know, it has to be obvious
right from the start.

00:39:17.470 --> 00:39:19.540
So the first point about Aqua,
I mean these are just some

00:39:19.570 --> 00:39:20.600
screens from Billings.

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:25.520
In the vein of keeping it easy to learn,
we had to make sure that every dialogue,

00:39:25.520 --> 00:39:27.340
every window was easily digestible.

00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:32.480
So one thing that the Aqua guidelines
talk about that good Mac OS X apps do

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:34.620
is they take advantage of white space.

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:36.600
They intelligently group controls.

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:39.510
No matter what kind of
dialogue you're doing,

00:39:39.510 --> 00:39:44.000
you can keep things easily
understandable by leaving a lot of space.

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:46.050
Don't crowd anything.

00:39:46.060 --> 00:39:48.690
Use standard controls and so on.

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:55.360
This point about starting on
paper is really important to me.

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:58.400
This is a scan of a sketchbook page.

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:01.080
And there's this line,
the pen is mightier than the mouse.

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:02.720
Yeah, it's very cheesy, so my apologies.

00:40:02.720 --> 00:40:04.880
But it's really important.

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:08.440
When you are planning your application,
it's great that, you know, for instance,

00:40:08.480 --> 00:40:09.070
IB is so fast.

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:11.600
You can drag out your controls,
you can start thinking about

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.020
your bindings right away.

00:40:13.020 --> 00:40:16.260
You can think about making an app almost,
you know, instantly.

00:40:16.260 --> 00:40:20.750
But what you're not doing is you're
not thinking twice or three times

00:40:20.750 --> 00:40:21.580
as you're pulling out your app.

00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:23.050
You're not pulling out these controls.

00:40:23.140 --> 00:40:24.830
You know,
I can lay out a dialogue like some of

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:26.880
the ones I showed you in five minutes,
maybe less.

00:40:26.880 --> 00:40:30.220
But to actually draw it on paper
takes quite a bit more time.

00:40:30.220 --> 00:40:32.210
And as I'm committing
my pen to the paper,

00:40:32.210 --> 00:40:34.520
drawing each button,
or drawing each window,

00:40:34.520 --> 00:40:36.700
as the case may be,
depending on how detailed

00:40:36.700 --> 00:40:39.570
you are with your sketches,
you're thinking twice.

00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:44.820
It's really hard to draw and write
out eight radio buttons on paper.

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:46.940
And as you're writing those
eight radio buttons out,

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:48.680
you'll be thinking, do I need this one?

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:50.030
Maybe not.

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:51.580
You know, maybe I can skip this
one and get by faster.

00:40:51.600 --> 00:40:53.600
Maybe this one doesn't really make sense.

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:57.740
So starting on paper is a really
great way to plan your app.

00:40:57.830 --> 00:40:59.530
And the most important thing about this,
really,

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:02.450
is that you can make mistakes now,
and you don't have to recode anything.

00:41:02.450 --> 00:41:05.220
You can just make mistakes
and show it to someone,

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:06.090
say, does this work?

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:07.900
No, no, you've got to move this around.

00:41:07.900 --> 00:41:09.800
You haven't actually invested in code.

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:11.340
You haven't invested in nibs.

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:13.000
You can just change it on paper.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.590
And once you have it planned, go digital.

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:20.450
And so the point about
keeping learning minimal,

00:41:20.470 --> 00:41:22.910
if there's anything extra in your UI,
it means that people have

00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:23.940
to learn something extra.

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:27.050
So focus on your core functionality.

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:30.420
Anything extra, get rid of it,
because people are just going to

00:41:30.420 --> 00:41:32.760
have to learn what that thing does,
and it's away from the

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:33.800
main purpose of the app.

00:41:33.870 --> 00:41:35.220
It's not focused.

00:41:35.220 --> 00:41:37.790
Progressive disclosure makes it
easy for users to get started.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:42.340
So like Jeff was just saying,
put certain things right up front,

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:46.430
but keep other things that maybe
are fringe case or for the 20% of

00:41:46.430 --> 00:41:49.340
users available but hidden away.

00:41:49.340 --> 00:41:53.010
We'll show these things later as people
become more comfortable with the app.

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:54.840
and use context-sensitive help.

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:56.900
Also,
Jeff showed that they have the tip window

00:41:56.900 --> 00:41:59.620
or the tip status bar in Real Basic 2005.

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:02.120
We do something kind
of similar in Billings,

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:03.330
which is we have a help box.

00:42:03.330 --> 00:42:08.350
When you first open the application,
certain areas of the interface are

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:12.480
described for you in an unobtrusive
box that will go away the next

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:14.840
time you use the application,
unless you want it.

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:17.820
What it does is it says,
"This is what this is for.

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:18.310
This is it.

00:42:18.420 --> 00:42:19.210
Now you know what it does.

00:42:19.250 --> 00:42:21.700
Now you don't have to
go get help anywhere.

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:23.700
Now you don't have to try to
figure out what this button does.

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:26.000
It's already explained for you.

00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:30.290
So again, keeping it simple,
like we did with Billings.

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:32.650
Focus on your users.

00:42:33.090 --> 00:42:37.300
Focus on a solution to your users' needs,
not a list of features.

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:40.290
And focus on a clean and
well-planned Aqua UI.

00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:41.960
Planning is everything.

00:42:42.010 --> 00:42:45.000
Get it done on paper first,
make sure that you're happy with it,

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:46.900
that your users are going
to be happy with it,

00:42:46.970 --> 00:42:47.940
and then move digital.

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:52.000
So I'd like to thank
John for having me up today.

00:42:57.820 --> 00:42:58.900
All right, that's part one.

00:42:58.900 --> 00:42:59.610
We've got to move fast.

00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:00.880
Determining your features.

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:02.600
Once you've got all that
stuff taken care of,

00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:05.320
the next question, of course,
is which technologies

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:08.130
do I use in Mac OS X,
and how do I prioritize them?

00:43:08.250 --> 00:43:10.640
And I'm going to bring
back something here,

00:43:10.640 --> 00:43:13.070
which I did years ago,
and I still today get

00:43:13.070 --> 00:43:14.820
requests for this chart.

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:18.680
And this is a modern version,
a new 2005 version of the chart,

00:43:18.680 --> 00:43:22.330
and hopefully it's a lot more
accurate than the one I did before.

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:26.300
But as you look at Aqua and over the
overall Mac OS X user experience,

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:28.630
you've got your thing figured out,
you know what features

