00:49:01.500 --> 00:49:03.540
and then go off and surprise and delight.

00:49:03.540 --> 00:49:05.090
All right.

00:49:05.230 --> 00:49:07.460
Let's get into the real
meat of this stuff.

00:49:07.810 --> 00:49:09.220
So design your user experience.

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:11.000
Design the interface for your product.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.380
This is all about
applying good techniques.

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:17.040
The first thing which is
really critical-- excuse me--

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:22.370
is to take-- you understand
who users are now.

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:25.030
The question is to ask, all right,
well what are they thinking about

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:26.360
when they're approaching this task?

00:49:26.370 --> 00:49:29.140
What are they thinking about when
they're starting to use this product?

00:49:29.300 --> 00:49:33.520
What are the concepts and
workflows and hierarchies of

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:35.200
objects and all of the things?

00:49:35.290 --> 00:49:38.040
What are the terms they're using,
and et cetera?

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:40.980
Get a handle on these things
because your main window,

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:43.420
your main UI,
the organization of your menus,

00:49:43.420 --> 00:49:46.900
the names of your utility windows,
your palette windows,

00:49:47.160 --> 00:49:52.780
everything that you do should be modeled,
should reflect that mental model.

00:49:52.810 --> 00:49:57.710
If I'm doing music jukebox stuff,
if I'm designing a jukebox player,

00:49:57.710 --> 00:50:01.140
like iTunes, if you ask somebody what
should that product have,

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:03.440
or what are the ideas
and concepts you've got,

00:50:03.440 --> 00:50:05.640
workflows,
they're going to talk about playing,

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:08.060
controls for playing the thing.

00:50:08.100 --> 00:50:11.640
They're going to talk about collections,
predominant,

00:50:11.700 --> 00:50:13.320
well-positioned in the main UI.

00:50:13.350 --> 00:50:15.410
They're going to talk about the
actual tracks that they play,

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:17.300
very, very dominate.

00:50:17.300 --> 00:50:19.310
It dominates the UI of iTunes.

00:50:19.450 --> 00:50:22.060
The main object users are
thinking about is music tracks,

00:50:22.080 --> 00:50:23.820
and it's there in the interface.

00:50:23.850 --> 00:50:25.550
And lastly,
some users might bring up the idea

00:50:25.550 --> 00:50:26.820
that they have to search for stuff.

00:50:26.820 --> 00:50:29.090
And so that's in the main UI interface.

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:32.240
But notice,
there's four components to iTunes.

00:50:32.290 --> 00:50:38.730
And that models the hierarchy and the
objects and the mental model that users

00:50:38.730 --> 00:50:39.970
have when they approach this product.

00:50:40.060 --> 00:50:42.560
Here's another example, iCal.

00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:43.340
Think about iCal.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:44.260
It's a calendaring tool.

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:46.730
Well, you need to have the ability
to have multiple calendars.

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:49.640
So that's featured very
clearly in the interface.

00:50:49.640 --> 00:50:51.480
You need to have the
actual calendar itself.

00:50:51.490 --> 00:50:53.540
Well, that dominates the interface.

00:50:53.560 --> 00:50:55.680
And then you have other things
like changing the month.

00:50:55.710 --> 00:50:57.000
And then simple controls.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:51:02.070
The most primary, most important,
most frequently accessed

00:51:02.140 --> 00:51:02.990
controls are in the UI.

00:51:03.020 --> 00:51:03.900
That's it.

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:05.520
That's it.

00:51:06.600 --> 00:51:07.500
All right, what else?

00:51:07.530 --> 00:51:08.700
Another example.

00:51:08.850 --> 00:51:09.940
Connoisseur.

00:51:09.940 --> 00:51:12.240
Great recipe management tool.

00:51:12.240 --> 00:51:13.960
You think about recipe
management on the computer,

00:51:13.960 --> 00:51:17.140
it's been the holy grail of
software since computers started.

00:51:17.140 --> 00:51:19.520
Everybody's writing about how
computers are great for recipes.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:22.910
Well, it seems like it's taken forever
for somebody to come up with this,

00:51:22.910 --> 00:51:25.050
and this product I think
comes really close.

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:29.410
They've got a great module for displaying
the recipe instructions in huge text,

00:51:29.410 --> 00:51:32.740
so you can have your power book
down on the countertop and you can

00:51:32.740 --> 00:51:34.820
be doing stuff and just look over.

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:36.450
You're not looking at
tiny text like this.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:40.300
But this is their navigation window,
and they've got the ability to organize

00:51:40.350 --> 00:51:42.950
all of their content in these playlists.

00:51:43.140 --> 00:51:45.840
They've taken the iTunes
and iPhoto playlist model.

00:51:45.840 --> 00:51:49.150
And then when you think about recipes,
well, you've got cuisine and the type

00:51:49.350 --> 00:51:52.360
of courses and the ingredients
and the actual recipes themselves,

00:51:52.530 --> 00:51:53.860
and that dominates the UI.

00:51:53.860 --> 00:51:54.340
That's it.

00:51:54.460 --> 00:51:56.500
They could have approached
this in a very different way,

00:51:56.560 --> 00:51:59.250
but they went about it this way,
and it really works for the product.

00:51:59.340 --> 00:52:01.050
SoftRaid.

00:52:01.180 --> 00:52:02.570
Software RAID solution.

00:52:02.670 --> 00:52:05.010
When you're talking about RAID,
you're talking about

00:52:05.030 --> 00:52:06.340
physical hard drives.

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:08.500
With hard drives with
wires and power supplies,

00:52:08.500 --> 00:52:11.460
and then on those hard drives you've
got logical volumes for the file system.

00:52:11.490 --> 00:52:14.500
Well, this is so dominant in the UI.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:15.430
It drives the point home.

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:18.140
Hard drives there,
connected to the disk menu.

00:52:18.140 --> 00:52:20.120
Left to right hierarchy of menus.

00:52:20.240 --> 00:52:22.440
So the first thing is the disk,
the physical device.

00:52:22.530 --> 00:52:24.420
On that physical device I've got volumes.

00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:27.270
So those are represented
in the UI very clearly.

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:32.080
And there's no misunderstanding by
the user which logical volumes are

00:52:32.080 --> 00:52:34.310
connected to which physical drives.

00:52:34.440 --> 00:52:36.440
The UI does a great job
of understanding that.

00:52:36.630 --> 00:52:40.160
The UI does a great job of driving,
of supporting the user's mental model.

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:41.640
And you need to be doing this.

00:52:41.640 --> 00:52:43.970
Every time I meet with a
company to do a UI review,

00:52:43.970 --> 00:52:46.500
I talk about what's the
user's mental model?

00:52:46.500 --> 00:52:47.500
How are you reflecting
that in your product?

00:52:47.500 --> 00:52:48.450
And it's amazing.

00:52:48.450 --> 00:52:50.880
We kind of do this churn,
and people think about it,

00:52:50.970 --> 00:52:52.950
and they don't know
what I'm talking about,

00:52:52.950 --> 00:52:55.680
and I explain it, we go through it,
and eventually a light

00:52:55.680 --> 00:52:59.530
bulb goes on and they go,
"Oh." And then suddenly when you get it,

00:52:59.530 --> 00:53:04.500
you realize your menus are disorganized,
the whole thing just falls into place.

00:53:04.500 --> 00:53:07.430
How many times have you looked
at your product and wondered,

00:53:07.520 --> 00:53:08.420
"Where do we stick this feature?

00:53:08.500 --> 00:53:13.320
Which menu does it go in?" You know,
and if that's ever occurred to you,

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:15.500
you've got something wrong
with the user mental model.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:17.360
Or with the way you're reflecting
the real world metaphors

00:53:17.460 --> 00:53:18.420
of the user mental model.

00:53:18.550 --> 00:53:20.800
So when you're designing
your main windows,

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:22.500
keep things simple and clean.

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:25.500
Don't overload the user with too
many controls and too many things.

00:53:25.500 --> 00:53:27.490
Think about what's the most important.

00:53:27.610 --> 00:53:29.500
Why is it on screen?

00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:32.500
What should be on screen
relative to what's not on screen?

00:53:32.500 --> 00:53:34.730
In other words,
if it's on the main screen,

00:53:34.810 --> 00:53:38.490
it should be something that
is frequently accessed.

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:41.500
Either every time you launch the
application and the window opens,

00:53:41.550 --> 00:53:43.980
every time the project is open,
let's say,

00:53:44.030 --> 00:53:45.490
or every time a selection is made.

00:53:45.500 --> 00:53:50.170
If it's highly, if it's frequently used,
it should be on the main interface.

00:53:50.510 --> 00:53:53.500
If it's not, then it should be elsewhere.

00:53:54.450 --> 00:53:56.700
Second point here is basically if
it's not important and shouldn't

00:53:56.700 --> 00:53:58.660
be on the main interface,
then it's a secondary item.

00:53:58.660 --> 00:53:59.880
It could be a tertiary feature.

00:53:59.880 --> 00:54:02.370
But for some reason,
even though the human eye reads

00:54:02.370 --> 00:54:04.610
from top left to bottom right,
in other words,

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:08.620
the top left corner is the most important
part of your application's interface,

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:13.440
the first thing I see in so many
apps is a preferences toolbar icon.

00:54:13.440 --> 00:54:15.700
It's like, well,
how often do I go to preferences?

00:54:15.790 --> 00:54:18.110
I shouldn't have to
go there often at all.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:23.200
And you've got the preference icon in the
most important spot on your interface?

00:54:23.780 --> 00:54:24.960
It just doesn't make any sense.

00:54:25.100 --> 00:54:27.860
So when you start to look at this stuff,
you realize, you know what?

00:54:27.940 --> 00:54:29.280
We can get rid of half these icons.

00:54:29.280 --> 00:54:31.380
They are so infrequently used,
they don't need to be there.

00:54:31.400 --> 00:54:34.760
So always ask when you're
looking at this whole process,

00:54:34.810 --> 00:54:39.340
what's important now in terms of the
context the user's in at that point?

00:54:39.800 --> 00:54:40.890
Anyway, there you go.

00:54:40.890 --> 00:54:42.060
Don't overload.

00:54:42.060 --> 00:54:43.350
Keep things fresh.

