00:56:09.140 --> 00:56:13.520
And each feature lives in this
home with its brothers and sisters.

00:56:13.580 --> 00:56:19.310
And this way if you know one feature,
you'll intuitively know where

00:56:19.310 --> 00:56:23.750
the brothers and sisters
for this feature live.

00:56:23.750 --> 00:56:23.750
It's like a...

00:56:24.620 --> 00:56:27.750
It's like in your kitchen where
you have your knives and your

00:56:27.750 --> 00:56:30.640
forks next to each other and you
have your spoons next to those.

00:56:30.740 --> 00:56:35.350
And so if a friend comes over
one day and they want a spoon,

00:56:35.350 --> 00:56:37.100
you tell them go to this
drawer and get a spoon.

00:56:37.140 --> 00:56:39.830
The next day they come over,
they don't need to ask you where

00:56:39.910 --> 00:56:43.560
to get a fork because they know it
lives next to the spoon intuitively.

00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:48.110
And so that's the concept behind
grouping your features like this.

00:56:48.970 --> 00:56:52.500
And so the first group we have
here is the collections area.

00:56:52.570 --> 00:56:55.900
And this is where our most
broad categories are stored.

00:56:55.980 --> 00:56:58.620
Stuff like just all your books,
all your movies,

00:56:58.700 --> 00:57:01.050
any collections that you've made.

00:57:01.540 --> 00:57:05.660
Then we have your borrowers area
where people you've added from your

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:09.460
address book go and you can check
stuff out to people right here.

00:57:09.550 --> 00:57:13.680
You just drag a book onto their
name and it checks it out to them.

00:57:13.880 --> 00:57:17.940
Then we have your bookshelf area and
this is where you browse all your books.

00:57:17.940 --> 00:57:20.090
And like John was saying,
this is the heart of our program.

00:57:20.090 --> 00:57:22.800
This is the star of the show right here.

00:57:22.800 --> 00:57:26.600
And in a screenshot you can just look
at our program and you immediately

00:57:26.730 --> 00:57:28.460
know what the software does.

00:57:28.500 --> 00:57:31.460
Because it jumps right out of
you and it's right in the center.

00:57:32.060 --> 00:57:34.780
And then we have the details area.

00:57:34.780 --> 00:57:37.940
And this is where you view
all the details about an item.

00:57:37.990 --> 00:57:38.970
And there's tabs at the bottom.

00:57:38.990 --> 00:57:40.000
There's three tabs.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:41.750
The first tab shows you
all the information we

00:57:41.810 --> 00:57:43.000
download from the internet.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.520
The second tab,
it shows you any information

00:57:45.520 --> 00:57:47.080
that you put in yourself.

00:57:47.080 --> 00:57:50.920
You can rate an item, you can put notes,
you can say if it's a rare item.

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:54.280
And then the third tab gives you
similar items so you can find

00:57:54.280 --> 00:57:56.200
new items that you want to buy.

00:57:56.200 --> 00:57:59.970
But those are all grouped under
one group because they're all

00:57:59.990 --> 00:58:01.970
information about one item.

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:05.180
And then we have this
button bar at the bottom.

00:58:05.180 --> 00:58:07.810
And this is where we thought
really hard about each button

00:58:07.810 --> 00:58:09.110
we're going to put on here.

00:58:09.110 --> 00:58:10.470
And we really refined this.

00:58:10.590 --> 00:58:13.390
So like John was saying,
we're putting only buttons that we use

00:58:13.390 --> 00:58:15.670
every single time you launch the program.

00:58:15.670 --> 00:58:19.880
And stuff that 20% of the people use,
we'll put up in the menu bar, you know.

00:58:19.880 --> 00:58:23.820
You don't need to put all
those right on your interface.

00:58:23.820 --> 00:58:26.440
And another thing to note
here is they're all underneath

00:58:26.440 --> 00:58:27.970
the group that they apply to.

00:58:27.970 --> 00:58:29.610
So you know when you
click the edit button,

00:58:29.700 --> 00:58:31.000
it's going to edit the details.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:31.980
And you know when you
click the edit button,

00:58:31.980 --> 00:58:31.980
it's going to edit the details.

00:58:32.040 --> 00:58:34.350
And you know when you click
the add collection button,

00:58:34.360 --> 00:58:35.900
it's going to add a collection.

00:58:35.900 --> 00:58:38.680
Some of our competition,
they have a big toolbar at the top.

00:58:38.680 --> 00:58:40.720
And they dump every single
one of their features into it.

00:58:40.810 --> 00:58:43.940
And it's in a total illogical order.

00:58:43.940 --> 00:58:46.510
And so you have no,
when you click something over here,

00:58:46.510 --> 00:58:47.940
it does something over here.

00:58:47.940 --> 00:58:50.590
You click something here,
it does something over here.

00:58:50.680 --> 00:58:52.590
With this,
you click it and it does exactly

00:58:52.590 --> 00:58:54.160
what you want right above it.

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:59.030
So, our interface is made
up of these five pieces,

00:58:59.030 --> 00:59:05.100
and I think that makes it really easy
to figure out and learn and predict

00:59:05.100 --> 00:59:08.710
where features are going to be once
you start learning the interface.

00:59:09.780 --> 00:59:12.960
So on top of having these groups,
these groups also flow

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:14.120
in a logical order.

00:59:14.180 --> 00:59:16.490
So when you click on Movies here,
it brings up all your

00:59:16.500 --> 00:59:18.040
movies in your bookshelf.

00:59:18.060 --> 00:59:20.980
And when you click on a movie,
it brings up all the movie

00:59:21.080 --> 00:59:23.020
details in the details area.

00:59:23.020 --> 00:59:27.680
And so as you move left to right,
we go from more general to more detailed,

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:31.820
and you drill down on the
information you're trying to find.

00:59:31.820 --> 00:59:33.840
And this makes it really
simple for people,

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:36.500
once again,
to predict the flow of your application.

00:59:37.360 --> 00:59:39.540
So once you click on Movies
and you see all the movies

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:42.470
appear under the bookshelf,
when you click on a borrower beneath,

00:59:42.470 --> 00:59:45.730
because it's right below the collections,
you'll intuitively know you're

00:59:45.790 --> 00:59:48.360
going to see all the items that
are checked out to that person,

00:59:48.470 --> 00:59:49.200
right?

00:59:52.930 --> 00:59:56.540
Then our bookshelf area here,
like I was saying before,

00:59:56.540 --> 00:59:58.500
it's the star of our program.

00:59:58.500 --> 01:00:02.180
It's what people first see when
they launch our program and

01:00:02.180 --> 01:00:07.730
it's how people interact with
the main part of our program,

01:00:07.730 --> 01:00:10.500
which is browsing all your collections.

01:00:10.560 --> 01:00:15.490
And lots of our competition
looks like this.

01:00:16.980 --> 01:00:20.700
And to us,
this was really just unacceptable.

01:00:20.720 --> 01:00:23.100
It wasn't going to do it, you know?

01:00:23.140 --> 01:00:25.340
If we put this out,

01:00:25.650 --> 01:00:28.820
I think our program would have just
blended in with everyone else's.

01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:30.260
It wouldn't have clicked.

01:00:30.360 --> 01:00:31.250
And it didn't click with us.

01:00:31.390 --> 01:00:32.870
You know, you look at this,
and this is how you're

01:00:32.970 --> 01:00:34.820
thinking of it as a developer,
right?

01:00:35.100 --> 01:00:38.840
When you're writing the software,
you have all this information,

01:00:39.120 --> 01:00:43.040
all this metadata on each one
of these items in a big list.

01:00:43.090 --> 01:00:46.210
And so you immediately think
this is the easiest way.

01:00:46.210 --> 01:00:49.180
You just drag it in from
Interface Builder and put all

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:51.400
this information in a big table.

01:00:51.400 --> 01:00:54.490
But we immediately realized
this isn't how people are used

01:00:54.490 --> 01:00:55.580
to interacting with Mac OS X.

01:00:55.610 --> 01:00:58.760
their media collections.

01:00:58.820 --> 01:01:01.640
They just took this item
off their bookshelf,

01:01:01.640 --> 01:01:04.700
scanned it, and--

01:01:05.300 --> 01:01:24.800
[Transcript missing]

01:01:25.340 --> 01:01:28.360
So we grouped our features.

01:01:28.380 --> 01:01:32.160
People understand where to find features
once they start using the program.

01:01:32.160 --> 01:01:33.840
And they're all in a predictable flow.

01:01:33.840 --> 01:01:36.650
And we use these real world metaphors.

01:01:36.680 --> 01:01:39.990
And it makes our program
really easy to use,

01:01:39.990 --> 01:01:41.100
really simple.

01:01:41.100 --> 01:01:46.740
And I think we've opened this kind of
product up to a much larger market now.

01:01:46.770 --> 01:01:51.030
Because it's much easier to use
and people are having fun with it.

01:01:51.150 --> 01:01:53.600
So thanks a lot.

01:01:54.070 --> 01:01:55.530
I hope you guys can learn from this.

01:02:01.370 --> 01:02:03.520
All right, lots of stuff so far.

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:05.390
You've seen three examples
of how developers have put

01:02:05.400 --> 01:02:06.120
this stuff into practice.

01:02:06.120 --> 01:02:07.480
Now we're going to get
really nitty gritty.

01:02:07.480 --> 01:02:09.220
The basics.

01:02:09.320 --> 01:02:13.800
Here's a checklist that any man,
any designer, any woman, any person,

01:02:13.800 --> 01:02:16.170
I call it every man's checklist,
but then a bunch of little

01:02:16.250 --> 01:02:18.750
women I work with said,
that's not the right name.

01:02:18.760 --> 01:02:20.440
So let's just call it The Checklist.

01:02:20.530 --> 01:02:22.460
This is The Checklist, capital The.

01:02:22.460 --> 01:02:25.000
You're going to get
these slides eventually,

01:02:25.130 --> 01:02:28.530
but this checklist is what you should,
anybody can do this.

01:02:28.680 --> 01:02:31.470
You know, not everybody is a Mike,
Mike Matos, right?

01:02:31.690 --> 01:02:33.200
Guy's incredibly gifted.

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:37.320
Not everybody's an Adam Baker,
incredibly gifted, you know, designer.

01:02:37.320 --> 01:02:41.100
There's lots of gifted designers,
but you guys maybe are, maybe aren't.

01:02:41.160 --> 01:02:42.000
I don't know.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.150
This list is the basics.

01:02:44.160 --> 01:02:46.090
If you get this down,
run through this checklist,

01:02:46.180 --> 01:02:48.920
every time you create a product,
you're going to get something good.

01:02:48.940 --> 01:02:51.040
Avoid using solid black,
75% black instead.

01:02:51.040 --> 01:02:52.080
You can read the screen.

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:53.370
Use white space effectively.

01:02:53.370 --> 01:02:55.400
I'm going to show you
the specific examples.

01:02:56.160 --> 01:02:58.920
Second part of the
checklist is label properly.

01:02:58.920 --> 01:03:01.200
Do the right thing with
the text on screen.

01:03:01.200 --> 01:03:04.350
Put colons after the, you know,
the label preceding a control.

01:03:04.490 --> 01:03:06.010
And then we're going to show
you how to align those things.

01:03:06.150 --> 01:03:07.200
Capitalize effectively.

01:03:07.200 --> 01:03:09.170
Avoid mixing text sizes, etc.

01:03:09.270 --> 01:03:11.920
I still see this stuff today,
even though we've made great

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:13.430
progress in the last five years.

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:17.230
And last point on the last bullet
was use user-centric terminology.

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:21.100
When you've determined the mental model
the customer has and their terminology,

01:03:21.100 --> 01:03:22.530
use their terms, not your terms.

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:27.480
Avoid mixing control styles, sizes,
text sizes.

01:03:27.480 --> 01:03:29.140
Avoid overriding and changing behaviors.

01:03:29.140 --> 01:03:30.390
If a push button,
if something looks like a push button,

01:03:30.390 --> 01:03:30.640
it better behave like a push button.

01:03:30.640 --> 01:03:37.010
So let's apply this checklist
to some real world examples.

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:39.810
Here's a dialogue from
a real Mac OS X app.

01:03:40.210 --> 01:03:40.620
Great app.

01:03:41.050 --> 01:03:42.800
Appreciate the developer
being on the platform.

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:44.380
But there's a whole bunch of issues here.

01:03:44.480 --> 01:03:47.660
Well, you know, at first glance,
you guys might say, well,

01:03:47.660 --> 01:03:49.170
it looks pretty good to me.

01:03:49.390 --> 01:03:51.430
Well, if you took the checklist
I just showed earlier,

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:53.120
for example, don't use solid black.

01:03:53.370 --> 01:03:56.260
Here's a redundant heading, first of all,
because the list already tells

01:03:56.340 --> 01:03:57.400
us what we're looking at.

01:03:57.400 --> 01:04:00.160
It tells us the name of the panel,
so why put it up there again?

01:04:00.330 --> 01:04:01.840
And it's unnecessary use of black.

01:04:01.930 --> 01:04:03.890
It's this big black bar.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:05.920
It's like, well,
that's not the look and feel of Mac OS X.

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:09.070
Mac OS X is much more subtle,
much softer in terms of

01:04:09.070 --> 01:04:10.280
presentation of information.

01:04:10.740 --> 01:04:12.400
What else is wrong here?

01:04:12.400 --> 01:04:15.770
Well, this list actually contains
a non-standard font.

01:04:15.800 --> 01:04:17.800
It's not the bolding of the
headings inside of the list.

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:21.930
The font itself doesn't match the
font on the right side of the screen.

01:04:22.600 --> 01:04:24.540
Another part of the checklist.

01:04:24.590 --> 01:04:25.290
Missing colons.

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:27.310
I told you put colons after labels.

01:04:27.470 --> 01:04:28.840
So there's missing
colons on those labels.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:32.220
By the way,
did you even know that those were labels?

01:04:35.860 --> 01:04:37.060
Misaligned and orphaned items.

01:04:37.080 --> 01:04:38.940
I don't know what those items belong to.

01:04:39.130 --> 01:04:41.380
I don't know which checkbox
they're connected with.

01:04:41.400 --> 01:04:44.060
They're just sitting out there
in the middle of nowhere,

01:04:44.060 --> 01:04:45.080
and I don't know what they are.

01:04:45.350 --> 01:04:47.530
So as a user, this is a problem.

01:04:47.530 --> 01:04:50.550
Because I glance at this dialog,
and I see lots of stuff,

01:04:50.550 --> 01:04:52.770
but I don't know,
it's not clearly organized.

01:04:52.780 --> 01:04:56.190
I often can't see things,
even though they might be right there.

01:04:56.190 --> 01:04:59.530
And it's a concept in interface
design called invisibility of items.

01:04:59.550 --> 01:05:02.890
You don't want things to be invisible,
and that's why the use of white space

01:05:02.890 --> 01:05:04.760
and margins is so important in Aqua.

01:05:04.760 --> 01:05:08.700
Because it lets you group things
so that people can find them.

01:05:08.720 --> 01:05:10.840
If they can't find them,
they're effectively invisible,

01:05:10.840 --> 01:05:11.460
is my point.

01:05:11.520 --> 01:05:13.580
Random non-standard
spacing between controls.

01:05:13.670 --> 01:05:17.840
You notice that each of these
highlighters is different sized.

01:05:17.900 --> 01:05:20.420
Just makes for a sloppy appearance.

01:05:20.460 --> 01:05:21.970
Misuse of white space.

01:05:21.970 --> 01:05:25.400
There's just honking, I mean,
just freeways of white

01:05:25.400 --> 01:05:27.220
space on this screen,
right?

01:05:27.220 --> 01:05:28.450
Why is that?

01:05:31.040 --> 01:05:32.940
Lastly, random button placement.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:34.100
I don't know why.

01:05:34.150 --> 01:05:35.900
I don't know why, right?

01:05:36.060 --> 01:05:37.460
This is the fun part of the session.

01:05:37.460 --> 01:05:41.380
So it's just, it's, and, and, you know,
I'm not picking on the developer, okay?

01:05:41.380 --> 01:05:43.040
I mean, really,
we appreciate the product.

01:05:43.040 --> 01:05:43.620
We really do.

01:05:43.620 --> 01:05:45.660
This is just a good example for
illustrating some of this stuff.

01:05:45.890 --> 01:05:46.790
Margins are too small.

01:05:46.790 --> 01:05:48.270
Stuff's too close to the edges.

01:05:50.490 --> 01:05:53.200
Alright, let's look at a renovated
version of that.

01:05:53.240 --> 01:05:55.990
So this is the same dialog redone.

01:05:55.990 --> 01:05:57.610
We did it here at Apple.

01:05:57.820 --> 01:05:59.380
And let's look at what's right.

01:05:59.970 --> 01:06:00.850
Proper margins.

01:06:01.180 --> 01:06:02.230
Notice the green means good.

01:06:02.440 --> 01:06:04.640
Go.

01:06:04.830 --> 01:06:06.710
Proper font.

01:06:09.460 --> 01:06:11.140
Right aligned labels.

01:06:11.160 --> 01:06:12.590
Notice the labels are all right aligned.

01:06:12.610 --> 01:06:16.650
They all are jagged on the left,
but the right side is nice and straight.

01:06:17.830 --> 01:06:19.540
Left-aligned controls.

01:06:19.550 --> 01:06:21.260
Notice they all stack
up real nicely there.

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:24.040
It looks really clean.

01:06:24.080 --> 01:06:26.320
How about spacing between items?

01:06:26.330 --> 01:06:28.870
Equal spacing between items.

01:06:31.780 --> 01:06:34.100
larger spacing between unrelated items.

01:06:34.170 --> 01:06:37.110
Now you'll see that the thicker
green bar is actually the same

01:06:37.110 --> 01:06:40.710
green bar as those upper two,
but it's on either side of that white,

01:06:40.890 --> 01:06:43.500
of the gray line there.

01:06:44.310 --> 01:06:44.800
Interesting.

01:06:44.950 --> 01:06:47.100
Same spacing,
but just put in there twice,

01:06:47.100 --> 01:06:51.490
and it shows you that there's two
distinct portions to the screen.

01:06:53.730 --> 01:06:56.000
and then finally we got rid
of the OK cancel in fact,

01:06:56.050 --> 01:06:58.070
and we just put a close
button on the window,

01:06:58.150 --> 01:06:58.600
right?

01:06:58.680 --> 01:07:00.770
Adds more modelessness
to the application,

01:07:00.770 --> 01:07:01.690
less modal dialog.

01:07:01.810 --> 01:07:04.630
OK and OK cancel is fine,
but in this case it was OK to do that.

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:06.700
Here's another panel for this dialog.

01:07:06.710 --> 01:07:08.940
Big problem here,
as soon as you see repeating

01:07:08.940 --> 01:07:11.650
interface like text that
repeats over and over and over,

01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:13.120
red flag, red flag, okay?

01:07:13.120 --> 01:07:15.390
You should instantly
start to say to yourself,

01:07:15.430 --> 01:07:16.560
what's wrong with it?

01:07:16.560 --> 01:07:17.510
Why am I doing this?

01:07:17.690 --> 01:07:20.870
In this particular case, well anyway,
we're running out of time and

01:07:20.870 --> 01:07:25.060
I don't have time to explain it,
but A lot of stuff going on

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:28.800
here and the solution was,
you know, there's too much redundancy.

01:07:28.800 --> 01:07:31.890
The solution was to kind of
redesign this thing and throw in

01:07:31.890 --> 01:07:35.640
a list because the list allows
for an unlimited number of items.

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:40.280
We can actually turn on and off the
item on the left with the checkbox.

01:07:40.280 --> 01:07:42.690
We can click on the row item
and add--click on the plus,

01:07:42.810 --> 01:07:45.400
minus to add rows,
and add the specific path by name or

01:07:45.400 --> 01:07:47.440
go and choose it from the file system.

01:07:47.440 --> 01:07:49.980
It just addressed a
whole bunch of issues.

01:07:50.530 --> 01:07:51.510
Big change.

01:07:51.510 --> 01:07:52.990
Here's another typical
scenario for clean up.

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:54.620
If you look at this screen,
it looks pretty good.

01:07:54.710 --> 01:07:56.120
Sort of.

