01:12:15.700 --> 01:12:18.570
But another area that's really
important to deliver a great

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:21.970
user experience in your product
is communicating effectively.

01:12:21.980 --> 01:12:23.840
And there are multiple
ways of communicating.

01:12:23.840 --> 01:12:26.620
The first thing to understand
is that this should parallel

01:12:26.620 --> 01:12:29.500
the human interaction,
the human experience, right?

01:12:29.500 --> 01:12:32.290
If you have somebody reporting to you,
you don't want them telling

01:12:32.290 --> 01:12:33.760
you about everything they did.

01:12:33.770 --> 01:12:35.610
Hey, boss, I went to get a coffee.

01:12:35.740 --> 01:12:38.460
Hey, boss,
got some staples for the staples.

01:12:38.460 --> 01:12:38.460
Hey, boss, stapled the report.

01:12:38.460 --> 01:12:38.460
Oh, hey, excuse me.

01:12:38.460 --> 01:12:38.460
I photocopied the report.

01:12:38.520 --> 01:12:38.960
Excuse me.

01:12:38.960 --> 01:12:40.080
I photocopied that thing for you, right?

01:12:40.170 --> 01:12:41.630
It's too much information, right?

01:12:41.640 --> 01:12:44.120
And the same thing is true for software.

01:12:44.120 --> 01:12:46.200
And actually, equally,
on the human experience side,

01:12:46.330 --> 01:12:48.530
you don't want an employee, you know,
you don't want to task

01:12:48.530 --> 01:12:50.410
somebody with something,
and then they run off,

01:12:50.410 --> 01:12:52.490
and you never hear from them
for three and a half months,

01:12:52.490 --> 01:12:54.770
and suddenly they're showing
up at your office door saying,

01:12:54.770 --> 01:12:57.280
well, actually,
it's not going to get done, you know?

01:12:57.280 --> 01:12:59.120
So that's too little information.

01:12:59.120 --> 01:13:01.030
And the same thing is true with software.

01:13:01.030 --> 01:13:04.570
Sometimes software just puts up too many
progress bars and too much information.

01:13:04.570 --> 01:13:06.920
I don't need to know the
byte count of the transfer.

01:13:06.920 --> 01:13:07.380
I just want to know whether it's,
you know,

01:13:07.420 --> 01:13:11.800
I just want to know whether it's going to
take another five minutes or something.

01:13:11.800 --> 01:13:15.600
So you can communicate non-intrusively
and non-interruptively.

01:13:15.600 --> 01:13:17.820
It's important to keep users
informed about what's going on,

01:13:17.820 --> 01:13:20.610
but you don't have to be modal and
jump in their face all the time

01:13:20.610 --> 01:13:22.080
and tell them what's going on.

01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:27.700
And so there's some appropriate
mechanism for communicating progress.

01:13:27.700 --> 01:13:29.620
A standard progress bar.

01:13:29.620 --> 01:13:30.660
A spinning gear.

01:13:30.660 --> 01:13:34.660
But just make sure you position
it in a place that's consistent

01:13:34.660 --> 01:13:37.420
and near maybe what the progress,
what specific is going on.

01:13:37.520 --> 01:13:39.710
So for example,
the download window in Safari or

01:13:39.730 --> 01:13:41.180
the spinning gears in Mail.

01:13:41.180 --> 01:13:44.730
You always look in the same spot to
see if Mail's going to do something,

01:13:44.730 --> 01:13:47.520
or beside the inbox
when it's checking Mail.

01:13:47.520 --> 01:13:49.570
iTunes has a voice level indicator.

01:13:49.640 --> 01:13:52.220
It doesn't keep putting up a modal
dialogue saying your voice is at level

01:13:52.320 --> 01:13:54.540
five or your voice is at level six.

01:13:54.540 --> 01:13:55.560
It does this kind of thing.

01:13:55.560 --> 01:13:59.560
It's non-interruptive.

01:13:59.960 --> 01:14:02.560
You can badge your dock icon.

01:14:02.590 --> 01:14:03.920
Hey, there's mail.

01:14:03.950 --> 01:14:05.000
You don't get anybody's way.

01:14:05.050 --> 01:14:06.400
The user notices the red dot.

01:14:06.540 --> 01:14:07.310
They pay attention.

01:14:07.340 --> 01:14:10.800
These are great ways to
communicate status to the users.

01:14:10.830 --> 01:14:13.540
But then there are times
where there are things occur,

01:14:13.540 --> 01:14:16.160
and you need to tell users
specifically what's going on.

01:14:16.180 --> 01:14:18.260
The first thing is if you
run into this situation,

01:14:18.260 --> 01:14:20.080
you should stop.

01:14:20.100 --> 01:14:23.000
If you get an error in your product,
you should stop and say, wait,

01:14:23.010 --> 01:14:27.710
can I redesign this thing so that the
error doesn't occur in the first place?

01:14:27.850 --> 01:14:31.310
When the original Mac was being designed,
there's a great story about how

01:14:31.310 --> 01:14:34.200
they were looking at the error
messages that came when people

01:14:34.320 --> 01:14:36.640
would pop the floppy disk out.

01:14:36.680 --> 01:14:40.090
And so people were saving, saving,
and they'd just go, oh, give me the CD.

01:14:40.200 --> 01:14:40.420
Boom.

01:14:40.460 --> 01:14:42.120
And the thing would go, oh, error.

01:14:42.120 --> 01:14:44.140
You can't save the file
because there's no floppy disk.

01:14:44.210 --> 01:14:45.820
So the designers started to think, well,
no, no, no.

01:14:45.820 --> 01:14:46.500
What can we do?

01:14:46.500 --> 01:14:49.680
And can we eliminate the condition
for the problem in the first place?

01:14:49.710 --> 01:14:52.750
And they ended up with the original
floppy disk drive that required

01:14:52.780 --> 01:14:56.640
you to first dismount the-- it
locked the thing in the drive.

01:14:56.690 --> 01:15:00.260
And so that just solved the
whole problem completely.

01:15:00.360 --> 01:15:03.370
So look to see if there's anything you
can do to get rid of the condition that

01:15:03.480 --> 01:15:04.820
caused the error in the first place.

01:15:04.880 --> 01:15:06.530
But if it has to be there,
because there are lots

01:15:06.630 --> 01:15:08.680
of cases where it is,
you should give good error

01:15:08.680 --> 01:15:12.900
messages and explain what happened,
why it happened, and what's the solution.

01:15:12.920 --> 01:15:16.720
All three of those are key
variables in that formula.

01:15:17.300 --> 01:15:20.900
So for example,
proper way to communicate.

01:15:20.920 --> 01:15:21.960
What happened?

01:15:21.990 --> 01:15:24.240
The trip document
request cannot be saved.

01:15:24.300 --> 01:15:24.710
Why?

01:15:24.740 --> 01:15:28.200
Because the disk work stuff is full.

01:15:28.240 --> 01:15:32.420
And then the solution is that.

01:15:32.450 --> 01:15:34.860
This is the wrong way to communicate.

01:15:35.620 --> 01:15:37.840
This is equally the
wrong way to communicate.

01:15:37.890 --> 01:15:42.480
There was a problem syncing your .Mac
account error code EFMS error 114.

01:15:42.520 --> 01:15:43.220
